Customer Segmentation using k-means Clustering¶

Customer segmentation is the practice of dividing a customer base into groups of individuals that are similar in specific ways relevant to marketing, such as age, gender, interests and spending habits.

For this project, I downloaded the mall customers dataset from Kaggle.

Dataset overview:

  • Customer ID: Id of customer
  • Gender: customer gender
  • Age: age of customer, we've got customers with age from 18 to 70 years
  • Annual Income: income of customer, will be renamed to income only, values from 13 to 137
  • Spending Score: Score assigned by the mall based on customer behavior and spending nature, values from 1 to 99

Data Preperation¶

Since Gender is a categorical variable with 2 values - Male and Female, one-hot encoding is used to convert male=1 and female=0. A new dataframe is created where age, income and score are normalized. This is done just to compare if there will be any difference in elbow method, however all columns except age has pretty much same values so we should not see anything extreme here

Using K-means Clustering¶

The first step is to find the ideal number of clusters using the elbow method.

Drawing inertia of KMeans on raw data and normalized data

In [13]:
# untransformed data
inertia = []
for i in range(1, 12):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=i).fit(df)
    inertia.append(km.inertia_)
    
# transformed data
inertia_t = []
for i in range(1, 12):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=i).fit(df_t)
    inertia_t.append(km.inertia_)

# plot results
plt.figure(figsize=(20,5))
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
sns.lineplot(x=range(1,12), y=inertia)
plt.title('KMeans inertia on original data')

plt.subplot(1,2,2)
sns.lineplot(x=range(1,12), y=inertia_t)
plt.title('KMeans inertia on transformed data')

plt.show()

When looking on inertia for original data: 2, 3 and 5 seems to be our candidates for number of clusters. When looking on inertia in transformed data, 2 and 4 seems to be best. So let us simply check how clustering looks like when using 2, 3, 4 and 5 clusters.

In [15]:
clusters = [2,3,4,5]
cluster_centers = {}

for c in clusters:
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=c).fit(df[['Age', 'Annual_Income', 'Spending_Score', 'Gender']])
    df['cluster' + str(c)] = km.labels_
    cluster_centers[str(c)] = km.cluster_centers_

Choosing the number of clusters for segmentation¶

Generally k-means clustering has between 2-5 clusters. Using 2 clusters would not help that much as it will only give two segments. When using 5 clusters, we are getting 5 different groups of customers that separates well from each other.

The number of clusters will change based on the business needs.

In [18]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20,15))
for i, c in enumerate(clusters):
    plt.subplot(2,2,i+1)
    sns.scatterplot(df.Annual_Income, df.Spending_Score, df['cluster' + str(c)], s=120, palette=sns.color_palette("hls", c))
    sns.scatterplot(cluster_centers[str(c)][:,1], cluster_centers[str(c)][:,2], color='black', s=300)
    plt.title('Number of clusters: ' + str(c))
    
plt.show()

From the above plot it is clearly evident that the plot with 5 clusters produces better results than other plots. Also the segments in the plot with 5 clusters are well seperated. So I will chose 5 as my number of clusters.
